<dl id="n33170f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n33" href="#n33170f">N33 (VI.B.4)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n33all.htm#n33170f"> 170(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ba heartsoul / ab heart <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n33170f"><li>FW 415.31f </li><li><a href="../../flex/pC/lexpC.htm#n33170f">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/pC/l39pC.htm#n33170f">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n33170f">MS Gilvarry-21</ms> </li><li>JJA not reproduced <a name="pCd3" href="../../ff/fdra/pda.htm#pCd3">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/pC/pCd3.htm#n33170f">Draft: III&sect;1C.3</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">3. The <mark><i>ba</i> &hellip;, or heart-soul</mark>, was in some way connected with the <i>ka</i>, in whom or with whom it was supposed to dwell in the tomb, and to partake of the funeral offerings, although in many texts it is made to live with R&acirc; or Osiris in heaven. It seems to have been able to assume a material or immaterial form at will &hellip;. &hellip; 4. The <mark><i>ab</i> &hellip;, or heart</mark>, was closely associated with the soul, and it was held to be the source both of the animal life and of good and evil in man. The preservation of the heart of a man held to be of the greatest importance, and in the Judgement it is the one member of the body which is singled out for special examination; here, &hellip; the heart &hellip; typifyies everything which the word &ldquo;conscience&rdquo; signifies to us. <small> E.A. Wallis Budge, <a name="BOD1" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#BOD1"><cite title="source">The Book of the Dead</cite></a>, 2nd ed. (1909) lxf</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: See also <a name="n47145e" href="n47all.htm#n47145e">N47 (VI.B.40):145(e)</a> </mm> </dd></dl>
